{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13795"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13795"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.05,0.1,0.75,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6412"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98130"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"118"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49743"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of left-sided facial weakness and itchiness in her left ear. She reports feeling generally unwell with a mild fever. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears mildly distressed with a temperature of 37.8\u00b0C. There is left-sided facial paralysis (Image 1) and a vesicular rash in the left external auditory canal (Image 2). The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral valaciclovir alone","Oral prednisolone alone","Intravenous acyclovir","Oral valaciclovir and prednisolone","Observation and supportive care"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with Ramsay Hunt syndrome, which is caused by reactivation of varicella-zoster virus in the geniculate ganglion. The most appropriate management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral valaciclovir and prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E. This combination therapy has been shown to be more effective than antiviral therapy alone in improving facial nerve function and reducing pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral valaciclovir alone\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for optimal management of Ramsay Hunt syndrome. While antivirals are crucial to treat the underlying viral infection, they do not adequately address the inflammatory component of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone alone\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it may potentially worsen the viral infection if used without antiviral coverage. Corticosteroids are important for reducing inflammation and potentially preventing long-term nerve damage, but they must be combined with antiviral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for severe cases or immunocompromised patients. For most immunocompetent patients with Ramsay Hunt syndrome, oral antiviral therapy is sufficient and more convenient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and supportive care\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate for Ramsay Hunt syndrome. Early treatment (within 72 hours of symptom onset) with combined antiviral and corticosteroid therapy is associated with better outcomes, including improved facial nerve recovery and reduced risk of postherpetic neuralgia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ramsay Hunt syndrome is caused by reactivation of varicella-zoster virus in the geniculate ganglion, requiring prompt antiviral therapy.","Combined antiviral and corticosteroid therapy is the most effective treatment for Ramsay Hunt syndrome.","Early treatment (within 72 hours of symptom onset) is associated with better outcomes in Ramsay Hunt syndrome."],"references":["Swan S, Tassone Y. Acute unilateral facial nerve palsy Case study [Internet]. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/bc2a8d1f-1213-4837-8f58-6ee228b62504/Acute-unilateral-facial-nerve-palsy.aspx","Goswami Y, Gaurkar SS. Ramsay Hunt Syndrome: An Introduction, Signs  and Symptoms, and Treatment. Cureus. 2023; 12; 15(1):e33688."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98130"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13795"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20736"},{"type":"media","id":"20737"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20736"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DMekzjFoBJeTmH0mtL9eN5XJmj3TBG.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DMekzjFoBJeTmH0mtL9eN5XJmj3TBG.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"media","id":"20737","links":{"self":"h